1150":"about 1150","about 1151":"about 1151","1259":"1259","1158":"1158","1246":"1246","1155":"1155","1232":"1232","about 1158":"about 1158","1131":"1131","1151":"1151","about 1155":"about 1155","about 1131":"about 1131","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Maud was born about 1131, in England, United Kingdom. She married William de Scotney about 1150, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 daughters."},"et":{"about 1131–":"umbes 1131–Surnud","–1232":"–1232","1151–1246":"1151–1246","1155–1259":"1155–1259","1158–Female":"1158–Surnud","1131–Female":"1131–Surnud","about 1150":"umbes 1150","about 1151":"umbes 1151","1259":"1259","1158":"1158","1246":"1246","1155":"1155","1232":"1232","about 1158":"umbes 1158","1131":"1131","1151":"1151","about 1155":"umbes 1155","about 1131":"umbes